If we forſake our ſins only in part, or commute one for another; if we leave ſome troubleſome and inconvenient Vices, and take up ſuch as ſeem more expedient;
if we avoid Swearing in common Diſcourſe, that our ſolemn Perjury may be leſs ſuſpected;Rom. 2. 22. if we abhor Idolatry, becauſe we deſire to commit Sacriledge; if we learn to ſuppreſs the Eruptions of
• aſh Anger, that our deſigned Revenge may at a fitter Opportunity be more ſecretly and effectually accompliſhed; what kind of Reformation is this? Can we think our ſelves grown better Men, by ſuch an Exchange and Bartering of ſins? Or, is not this rather the very Policy and Subtilty of Wickedneſs, whereby we diſcover our deeper Skill in the Trade and Myſtery of Iniquity?
